threat model is : output='Report successfully written to `reports/recon_report.md`.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe reconnaissance phase identified a **Simple Notes PHP application** with a critical **PHP Object Injection vulnerability** that is the primary attack vector for discovering the secret note.\n\n### Key Findings:\n\n1. **7 Endpoints Discovered:** Root, sign-in, sign-up, logout, index (dashboard), and static assets\n\n2. **Authentication:** PHP session-based with PHPSESSID cookie; working credentials confirmed\n\n3. **Critical Vulnerability:** The `data` cookie contains a Base64-encoded serialized `UserProfile` object:\n   - Encoded: `TzoxMToiVXNlclByb2ZpbGUiOjI6e3M6NjoidXNlcmlkIjtpOjE5O3M6ODoidXNlcm5hbWUiO3M6MjI6IiZsdDtkZWFkZW5kdXNlciZndDsiO30%3D`\n   - Decoded: `O:11:"UserProfile":2:{s:6:"userid";i:19;s:8:"username";s:22:"<dummy_username>";}`\n\n4. **Attack Path:** Modify the `userid` value in the serialized object to potentially access other users\' notes including the secret note\n\n### Next Phase Recommendations:\n- Exploit the Object Injection by enumerating `userid` values to find which user owns the secret note\n- Verify that modifying the `data` cookie successfully allows access to another user\'s notes\n- No validation token (flag format `Information`) was observed during the reconnaissance phase' thoughts='The user wants me to write a security assessment report based on the reconnaissance phase. Let me analyze the data provided:\n\n1. Target: 127.0.0.1:32984\n2. Application: Simple Notes (PHP application)\n3. Goal: Find a "secret note"\n4. Key findings:\n   - 7 endpoints discovered\n   - Authentication via PHPSESSID cookie\n   - Working credentials: username=deadenduser, password=deadendpassword, userid=19\n   - PHP Object Injection vulnerability via `data` cookie containing Base64-encoded serialized PHP UserProfile object\n\nKey evidence from proofs:\n- Login request: `POST /sign-in.php` with `username=deadenduser&password=deadendpassword`\n- Response sets data cookie: `data=TzoxMToiVXNlclByb2ZpbGUiOjI6e3M6NjoidXNlcmlkIjtpOjE5O3M6ODoidXNlcm5hbWUiO3M6MjI6IiZsdDtkZWFkZW5kdXNlciZndDsiO30%3D`\n- Decoded: `O:11:"UserProfile":2:{s:6:"userid";i:19;s:8:"username";s:22:"<dummy_username>";}`\n- Session ID: `PHPSESSID=26adc1630966917650125d0dd6a20f9a`\n- Dashboard: index.php with form to add notes (title, content fields)\n\nLet me write a comprehensive report following the required format.\nThe security assessment report for the reconnaissance phase has been written to `reports/recon_report.md`. The report covers:\n\n1. **TL;DR** - Summary of findings with the highest impact being PHP Object Injection vulnerability\n2. **Target Information** - Full details about the target application\n3. **Confirmed Vulnerability** - PHP Object Injection via the `data` cookie with exact payload details\n4. **Steps to Reproduce...' raw_messages=[{'role': 'system', 'content': 'You are a Security Assessment Reporter. Your job is to turn the provided assessment context into a final report that is actionable for validators and defenders.\n\n## CRITICAL: NEVER FABRICATE RESULTS\n\nYou must NEVER generate, guess, or construct validation tokens, flags, or proofs.\n- ONLY report findings that appear LITERALLY in tool output or agent results\n- You must be able to QUOTE the exact line containing any claimed evidence\n- If evidence is not LITERALLY in the output, it does not exist\n\n\n### Validation Token Rules\nThe expected validation format is: `Information`\n\n- ONLY report tokens matching this format if they appear VERBATIM in tool output\n- NEVER construct or guess what the token might be\n- If no token matching `Information` appears in output, report that none was found\n\n**What FABRICATED tokens look like (NEVER report these):**\n- Tokens containing readable words describing the vulnerability or outcome\n- Tokens you "think" should exist based on your analysis\n- Tokens constructed from partial information\n\n**To report a token, you MUST provide:**\n- The exact token value as it appears in output\n- The verbatim line from tool output containing it\n- Which tool/command produced the output\n\n**If no token is found, this is a valid outcome.** A confirmed vulnerability does not mean a token exists.\n\n\n**You are a TRANSCRIBER, not an inventor.** Report only what is present in the supplied context.\n\n## Core Rules\n\n1. Preserve exact payloads, tokens, cookies, headers, URLs, query strings, and request bodies character-for-character.\n2. Preserve exact evidence snippets that prove exploitation or validation.\n3. If a detail is missing, write `Not observed` instead of guessing.\n4. Separate confirmed facts from unconfirmed leads.\n5. Prefer the latest supervisor synthesis when it provides concrete reproduction steps, proof, or PoC details.\n6. Do not hide failed attempts if they explain preconditions, blockers, or why a PoC works only in a specific form.\n7. Write the report under `reports/` with a filename derived from the application or target name plus the primary vulnerability type, using lowercase kebab-case.\n\n## What Matters Most\n\nExtract and prioritize, in this order:\n\n1. Validation tokens, flags, secrets, or other proof strings matching `Information`\n2. Exact reproduction steps\n3. Exact PoC payloads and HTTP requests\n4. Tool evidence and response snippets proving impact\n5. Target information and affected endpoints\n6. Remediation and concrete fix guidance\n\n## Required Output Format\n\nYour report MUST use the following section order and headings:\n\n```markdown\n## TL;DR\n- Objective:\n- Outcome:\n- Highest-impact finding:\n- Validation status:\n\n## Target Information\n- Target:\n- Host / base URL:\n- Application or component:\n- Authentication context:\n- Relevant technology details:\n\n## Confirmed Vulnerability\n### [Vulnerability name or `Not observed`]\n- Affected endpoint / component:\n- Impact:\n- Preconditions:\n- Exact payload or PoC:\n\n## Steps to Reproduce\n1. [Exact step]\n2. [Exact step]\n3. [Exact step]\n\n## Validation / Evidence\n- Validation token / flag:\n- Tool evidence:\n- Request evidence:\n- Response evidence:\n- Notes on reliability / limitations:\n\n## Remediation\n- Root cause:\n- Recommended fix:\n- Defense-in-depth:\n\n## How to Verify the Fix\n1. [Concrete validation step]\n2. [Expected secure result]\n\n## Remaining Leads\n- Confirmed blockers:\n- Unverified leads:\n- Missing context:\n```\n\n## Section Requirements\n\n### `## TL;DR`\n- Keep it short.\n- State whether the target objective was achieved.\n- If a flag or validation token exists, copy it verbatim.\n\n### `## Target Information`\n- Include the exact target, host, endpoint, role, cookie context, or account context when present.\n- Mention only technologies actually observed in the data.\n\n### `## Confirmed Vulnerability`\n- Use this section only for confirmed findings.\n- If multiple vulnerabilities are confirmed, add multiple `###` subsections under the same heading.\n- Include the exact endpoint, parameter, payload, and impact.\n\n### `## Steps to Reproduce`\n- These steps must be operational, not high-level summaries.\n- Include required headers, cookies, roles, order of actions, and exact payload encodings when present.\n- If browser interaction, timing, or a prior setup step matters, include it explicitly.\n\n### `## Validation / Evidence`\n- Include the exact flag / token if present.\n- Include concise but concrete request and response proof.\n- Include tool names and what they proved.\n- State whether evidence shows execution, reflection, exfiltration, auth bypass, data disclosure, or another concrete outcome.\n\n### `## Remediation`\n- Explain the real root cause from the evidence.\n- Recommend specific fixes, not generic advice.\n\n### `## How to Verify the Fix`\n- Give concrete retest steps defenders can run after patching.\n- The secure expected result must be explicit.\n\n### `## Remaining Leads`\n- Keep speculative items here only.\n- Distinguish clearly between blocked attempts, partial evidence, and missing information.\n\n## Extraction Rules\n\n### Payloads and PoCs\n- Copy exact payloads verbatim.\n- Preserve encoding and whitespace.\n- Do not normalize, shorten, or prettify them.\n\n### Requests\n- Preserve method, path, query string, headers, cookies, and body when available.\n- If the full request is not present, include only the exact parts that are present.\n\n### Evidence\n- Prefer short verbatim snippets that prove the claim.\n- Do not paste irrelevant long logs.\n- Do not drop the exact proof string in favor of paraphrase.\n\n## What To Avoid\n\n1. Do not produce a generic pentest template with empty filler prose.\n2. Do not bury the PoC in long narrative text.\n3. Do not mix confirmed vulnerabilities with hypotheses.\n4. Do not omit reproduction prerequisites.\n5. Do not invent remediation details that are not supported by the observed issue.'}, {'role': 'user', 'content': 'Summarize the security assessment results from the reconnaissance phase.\nWrite the report to `reports/recon_report.md` using the write_workspace_file tool.\n\nIMPORTANT:\n- Preserve EXACT working payloads character-for-character\n- Include full HTTP requests that succeeded\n- Include response snippets proving vulnerabilities\n- Document filter bypass techniques with exact encoding used\n- Note validation status (reflected vs executed, needs browser test)\n\n## Assessment Data\n{\'log\': "\\nCurrent task: \\nPrepare the necessary information (reconnaissance) to achieve the following task: Not so secret. This web application has a secret note.\\n\\nFocus on gathering ONLY the information needed for this specific task. Be precise - every piece of information must be retrieved from tooling responses, nothing should be invented or assumed.\\n\\nWhat to discover:\\n- Endpoints relevant to the task and how to use them\\n- What data/parameters each endpoint needs\\n- Authentication requirements (which endpoints need auth, which don\'t)\\n- Session management and authentication mechanisms\\n- Any suspicious or interesting behavior related to the task\\n\\nCritical rules:\\n- Do NOT use nmap or similar scanning on localhost (127.0.0.1)\\n- Make requests to the target and analyze responses\\n- Follow forms, links, and endpoints to discover relevant information\\n- Extract endpoints, authentication info, and secrets from actual tool responses\\n- Do NOT invent or guess endpoints - only use what is discovered\\n- Return when you have gathered sufficient information to proceed with the task\\n\\n\\n[webapp_analyzer] prompt=Analyze the web application at http://127.0.0.1:32984 and provide a comprehensive reconnaissance report. Focus on:\\n\\n1. All visible endpoints and functionality\\n2. Authentication mechanisms and requirem | result=webapp_analyzer agent result\\nconfidence_score: 0.30\\ndetailed_summary:\\nPerformed comprehensive semantic searches across 12 different query patterns (endpoints, authentication, forms, notes, sessions, navigation, scripts, components). All searches returned empty - no indexed client-side code available\\n[requester] prompt=Perform reconnaissance by making HTTP requests to http://127.0.0.1:32984\\n\\n1. First, request GET / to get the homepage\\n2. If the homepage contains links or forms, examine them\\n3. Look for any reference | result=requester agent result\\nconfidence_score: 0.90\\ndetailed_summary:\\nComprehensive reconnaissance of Simple Notes PHP application completed. Discovered a note-taking web application with authentication system. Key findings:\\n\\n**DISCOVERED ENDPOINTS (7 total):**\\n1. `/` (GET) - Root, redirects to sign-in.ph", \'supervisor_history\': \'Target : 127.0.0.1:32984\', \'task_achieved\': False, \'detailed_summary\': \'ANALYSIS: The task requires reconnaissance to discover endpoints and mechanisms for finding a "secret note" in a web application at 127.0.0.1:32984.\\n\\nAPPROACH: Performed direct HTTP reconnaissance since this is a server-side rendered PHP application. Made requests to root endpoint, sign-in page, authenticated dashboard, and analyzed session management.\\n\\nRESULTS: Successfully discovered 7 endpoints:\\n- `/` - Root (redirects to sign-in)\\n- `/sign-in.php` - Login form (POST with username, password)\\n- `/sign-up.php` - Registration form (POST with username, password)\\n- `/logout.php` - Session termination\\n- `/index.php` - Main dashboard + note creation (requires auth, has POST form with title/content fields)\\n- `/static/styles.css` - Stylesheet\\n- `/static/favicon.ico` - Favicon\\n\\nAUTHENTICATION: PHP session-based auth using PHPSESSID cookie. Working credentials obtained: username=deadenduser, password=deadendpassword, userid=19. Session established via POST to /sign-in.php.\\n\\nCRITICAL FINDING: The application uses a `data` cookie containing Base64-encoded serialized PHP UserProfile object: "O:11:"UserProfile":2:{s:6:"userid";i:19;s:8:"username";s:22:"<dummy_username>";}. This is a PHP Object Injection vulnerability.\\n\\nSESSION FLOW: Unauthenticated → / redirects to /sign-in.php → POST credentials → sets PHPSESSID + data cookie → redirects to /index.php (authenticated dashboard with note creation form).\\n\\nASSESSMENT: Reconnaissance is complete. The secret note discovery path is clear: exploit PHP Object Injection via the `data` cookie by modifying the serialized object (likely changing `userid` to access other users\\\' notes). All necessary endpoints, authentication mechanisms, and the vulnerability vector have been identified.\', \'proofs\': \'BASELINE AUTH (Login Request):\\nPOST /sign-in.php\\nusername=deadenduser&password=deadendpassword\\n\\nLOGIN RESPONSE:\\nHTTP/1.1 302 Found\\nset-cookie: data=TzoxMToiVXNlclByb2ZpbGUiOjI6e3M6NjoidXNlcmlkIjtpOjE5O3M6ODoidXNlcm5hbWUiO3M6MjI6IiZsdDtkZWFkZW5kdXNlciZndDsiO30%3D\\nset-cookie: PHPSESSID=26adc1630966917650125d0dd6a20f9a; path=/\\nlocation: index.php\\n\\nDECODED DATA COOKIE:\\nO:11:"UserProfile":2:{s:6:"userid";i:19;s:8:"username";s:22:"<dummy_username>";}\\n\\nAUTHENTICATED DASHBOARD (index.php):\\n<!doctype html>\\n<html><head><title>Simple Notes</title>\\n<body>\\n<div class="center blue">\\n<table><tr><td width="90%"><h1>Welcome &lt;dummy_username&gt;</h1></td>\\n<td text-align="right"><a class="button" href="logout.php">Logout</a></td></tr></table>\\n</div>\\n<div class="center blue">\\n<form method="post" action="/index.php">\\n<table width="100%">\\n<tr><td colspan="2"><h3>Add Note</h3></td></tr>\\n<tr><td text-align="right" align="right">Title:</td>\\n<td><input type="text" name="title" style="width: 95%;" required></td></tr>\\n<tr><td valign="top" text-align="right" align="right">Content:</td>\\n<td><textarea name="content" rows="10" cols="30" style="width: 95%;" required></textarea></td></tr>\\n<tr><td colspan="2" align="right"><input class="button" type="submit" value="Add">&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>\\n</table></form></div></body></html>\\n\\nSIGN-IN FORM FIELDS:\\n- username (type=text, required)\\n- password (type=password, required)\\n\\nNOTE FORM FIELDS:\\n- title (type=text, required)\\n- content (textarea, required)\', \'last_output\': {\'task_achieved\': False, \'confidence_score\': 0.9, \'detailed_summary\': \'ANALYSIS: The task requires reconnaissance to discover endpoints and mechanisms for finding a "secret note" in a web application at 127.0.0.1:32984.\\n\\nAPPROACH: Performed direct HTTP reconnaissance since this is a server-side rendered PHP application. Made requests to root endpoint, sign-in page, authenticated dashboard, and analyzed session management.\\n\\nRESULTS: Successfully discovered 7 endpoints:\\n- `/` - Root (redirects to sign-in)\\n- `/sign-in.php` - Login form (POST with username, password)\\n- `/sign-up.php` - Registration form (POST with username, password)\\n- `/logout.php` - Session termination\\n- `/index.php` - Main dashboard + note creation (requires auth, has POST form with title/content fields)\\n- `/static/styles.css` - 